eventName: Virtual Lands end to John o Groats
story: Sal and I have been running for nearly 10 years, it was all her idea! I was never the cross country champ at school in fact I was always last, but running with Sal (not forgetting my fur babies) gives it a whole new enjoyability! We want to keep challenging ourselves and felt that this was a great way to increase the challenge and raise money for a fabulous cause. We have both been affected by Cancer in our families and one of our closest friends lost her husband from this dreadful disease in Jan 2020 so please dig deep and encourage this mammoth task we have undertaken! It begins on the 1st of January and we aim to run (virtually) from Lands end to John O Groats thats 874 miles by the 31st Dec!

story:
Thank you for visiting my just giving page...

If anyone knows me they know I love a drink, doesn’t matter what kind I’ll have it. That’s why I’ve decided to take part in Dry jan and not have a drop of alcohol! (Ekk) 

As most of my friends and family know my mum was diagnosed with breast cancer in 2019 ,safe to say our whole world feel a part, she had rounds of chemo/ radiotherapy and 3 operations including a serious spinal surgery. 

Myself my sister & my mum ( while having cancer treatment) did the shine walk raising money for breast cancer UK. We raised over £3,000, I want to make it my mission to help support charity’s like this.

I’m raising money for Macmillan cancer support as through out my mums cancer journey they have been amazing, the appointments/ the phone calls and just the staff who work for Macmillan. 

I know times are tough at the moment with covid and people being out of walk but I would be so great full  for any donation to such an amazing charity so close to my heart! 

Thank you 

Daisy xx

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Dear family and friends

As I approach 2021 and my 56th birthday in March  I wanted to do more in terms of helping support a worthy cause (despite a number of other worthy causes) - Macmillan Cancer Care. This is because cancer has adverse impacted my family and dear friends. My cousin ‘rest in peace sister’ passed away few years ago within months of her diagnosis. My grand father was afflicted with cancer of pancreas passed away earlier than expected. My father in law also passed away after developing cancer on top of other ailments therefore wasn’t strong enough to be treated. There are a number of friends who have successfully come through treatment for breast cancer - very thankful. No doubt cancer has touched all of us directly or indirectly.

Therefore I would be very grateful for your donation - little or large. Above all I appreciate your support, your smile, your encouragement  and positive vibes. 

I am aiming to raise £2000 by running 300km over 3 months - Jan21 to Mar21. I will keep you updated on progress. If I can do this anyone can. Very grateful if you could forward link to my ‘just giving’ page to your network.

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, they are right right there with you. Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. Thanks!

This charity is close to my heart ❤ My son Lewis was born with 2 heart defects undetected. At 3 months old due to a routine appointment they were found in which time he was struggling for breath and unable to feed normally. After 2 years of constant hospital admissions and ending in 2 heart operations one being open heart surgery he finally started to live a normal life. I would like to give back as during our stays in London Royal Brompton we were given help and support in many different ways. I would like more training to be given and more high tech scanners used during ultrasounds in pregnancy to ensure these heart conditions aren't missed. Please give as much as you can, it really is a amazing charity that have struggled during the pandemic to raise vital funds ❤ I am skydiving in memory of my dear friend Daisy who we sadly lost due to a skydiving accident. Its taken me many years to gain the courage to do this. I won't be skydiving on my own so it is very different but I know he will be looking down on me proud 🙏 thankyou for your support x


Sky dive due to happen 13/02/21 (weather permitted)

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Welcome to my Just Giving fundraising page! On the 30th May 2021 I will be joining the British Heart Foundation team running in the Edinburgh Marathon. The foundations vision of a world free from the fear of heart and circulatory diseases is one I deeply share.

Heart diseases, strokes, and vascular dementia are not only the biggest killers in the UK, but worldwide, affecting 1 in 4 people. Your donations will go towards life saving research as well as support for the families and patients who continue to battle these diseases daily. 

Unfortunately this race is much more personal for me than simply donating to an incredible charity like the BHF. Over the years I have witnessed first hand the heart breaking consequences of these diseases having lost three of my grandparents to them. Most recently my dad also suffered a heart attack, further underlining to me the importance of the foundations research.

Come 30th May I won’t just be running for my family but for the thousands of people across the UK who are personally affected by these diseases. 

Any donations no matter how small are greatly appreciated!

Much love, Grant

I am raising this money in memory of my mum who passed away ultimately due to a cardiac arrest. I am forever missing her and thought I would do something that could help prevent others from having to miss family members x 

To help raise awareness and money for research and CPR to be taught more regularly. CPR can double the chance of survival until an ambulance is reached so is SO important people know how to do this. 

30,000 people have a cardiac arrest each year in the UK and this costs the NHS between £50-65,000 for each survivor/non-survivor. 

So any support and donations would go a long way and be extremely appreciated. 

I will swimming in southend beach  water once week for the whole of February and also recreating some photos of my mum. 


Yes it will be freezing and I will definitely regret it but... a good cause right?!

My Nan suddenly passed away from a heart attack in March 2019. This came as a sudden almighty shock. My nan appeared healthy, she moaned about many things (don’t we all). Then we lost her. Breaking all our hearts as she went. 

Although we couldn’t have changed things, we can now help to fund research and treatments.

We have all been stuck in more than we would have wanted this past year, so this year with my pram and Ronnie! I am settling myself a target to walk 350 miles at least! Before March 23rd.  

Rain, wind or snow I will get out and try to do my bit! 

Please help me by donating any amount to this wonderful cause. 

Every little helps :)

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Heart and Circulatory diseases cause 1 death every 3 minutes in the UK. That is 460 deaths per day, 170,000 deaths per year. 

Thank you for visiting my page. This February I have decided to walk 1 mile every day for 27 days, then 15 miles on the 28th day. 

My Grandad died suddenly on holiday in 2011 after a heart attack induced cardiac arrest. Some years later his brother also passed in the same horrific way. My best friend, my Nana was diagnosed with severe heart failure last year, and has since been fitted with an ICD (Implantable Cardioverter Defibrillator) and has had support from BHF Nurses in a hospital setting. In October this year my other Grandad had a heart attack induced cardiac arrest at home and spent several weeks in a coma, although he is now out of the coma and doing better than he was, there is a lot of life adjustments for him to process and a long road of recovery ahead. 

There are more than 30,000 out-of-hospital cardiac arrests in the UK each year. The survival rate is just 1 in 10.

The facts are staggering and it affects people of all ages. Not only our family but thousands of other families are absolutely devastated by heart and circulatory deaths and diseases. 

The British Heart Foundation funds over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Furthermore, they support people with heart and circulatory diseases through several means including an online community, and specialist nurse occupied telephone lines. The BNF also offers detailed advice and guidance on the diseases and their risk factors. 

For every £1 raised, around 72p, went straight to funding research.

Due to the heartbreak these diseases have caused to my family, other families and COVID-19 cutting the BHF ability to fund new research in half... I have decided I want to do everything I can to help this cause. This charity has and will continue to save lives, it’s facts. 

Please help me hit my target of £250.00, every penny counts. Thank you so much in advance, this cause is so close to my heart. 

❤️I PLEDGE TO WALK 1 MILE EVERYDAY FROM 1st TO 27th FEBRUARY 

❤️ ON THE 28th FEBRUARY I WILL WALK FROM MANCHESTER ROYAL INFIRMARY TO WESTHOUGHTON TOWN HALL - 15 miles

* 1 mile may not seem much to some, but anybody who knows me will know I don’t really exercise at all and I will do anything out of having to walk anywhere. I am an unhealthy weight,  I smoke, I drink, and I don’t exercise much... I have 4 risk factors that could contribute to my own heart or circulatory problems in the future and I hope this fundraiser will not only raise money for a brilliant cause but change my attitude and lifestyle too.

*I hope that by 28th Feb my Grandad is no longer in Manchester Royal Infirmary, I hope he is back home with us. But, I would like to walk from there as that’s where he has spent the most time whilst he has been poorly, to our hometown town hall in Westhoughton, Bolton.

❤️I will update everyone daily on how it’s going via this page and my Instagram @molliekilcoynex❤️ 

Thankyou so much, Mollie x

❣️

In memory of, 

Eddie Kilcoyne & John Kilcoyne 

In support of, 

Jim Tyrer & Jean Tyrer  

❣️

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. 

Many of you will be aware that when my Dad died suddenly 7 years ago this coming March. I signed up to run for the BHF in his memory. 

Sadly I then broke my foot badly and it was not to be - I always said I would run again in his memory, but my health was not good and my recovery was slow with my foot. Now I feel it’s time to stop the excuses and get training, improve my own health and do it!

I’ve given up smoking, largely reduced my alcohol intake and I am ready mentally and physically to give my children a better chance of me surviving longer than the 69 years that my Dad had!

And what better place to do it than where my Mum’s Mum was born! 

I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation as I’ve said and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target.

I’m fully aware that people are struggling financially with Covid having hit people hard - but even if you could share my page and even sponsor me £1 every pound would help!! 

Much love Dawn xx

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting our page!

My brother, Chris and I will be running a half marathon every week of May 2021 up until the London Landmarks Half Marathon on Sunday 23rd May, which will be our last half! 

We’ll be taking on this challenge to raise money for the British Heart Foundation, a charity incredibly close to our hearts. 

In 2010, our mum, Hilary, suffered a life threatening cardiac arrest due to a (unknown to her at the time) genetic heart condition called Long QT Syndrome. It was the scariest moment of our lives and we were very close to losing her. My brother, Chris, distributed life-saving CPR to our mum, having been taught it at Cadets. The British Heart Foundation campaign tirelessly for more education on CPR techniques, and in our case, had my brother not been there at the time, things may not have turned out as well as they did for us. We are so fortunate that our mum made a miraculous full recovery from the cardiac arrest. Our family and our mum individually were supported greatly by the BHF following the event and we are huge advocates of their work. 

We would be so grateful if you are able to donate money for this amazing cause no matter how small; we really appreciate it! 

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like you that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. I hope you’re able to join us in supporting this amazing charity!!

Thank you so much,

Fran and Chris

story:
The year 2020 was terrible for so many people. We experienced toilet paper panic- buying, social distancing, lockdowns, elbow-bump greetings, and Zoom meetings and funerals.

As a result, I’ve decided to do whatever possible to support charities in 2021.I would like to support charities to recoup some of the money they were unable to make and, at the same time, stay fit and healthy both mentally and physically.

I am setting myself a challenge to raise money for different charities throughout the year. My 1st challenge is to run 31 miles during January in support of Great Ormond Street Hospital.

I never liked running. However, I roped my friend into joining me in achieving the couch to 5k challenge by Christmas, but sadly it didn’t happen. To complete our challenge of getting to 5k,  I figured doing it for charity makes it even more worthwhile.  

I don’t have a personal connection to Great Ormond Street Hospital. However, I am aware of the excellent work they do in supporting children and families, with sick children fulfilling their potential.  As a teacher, I believe we should put children first because they are our future, and this challenge is a great way to support them.

Please join me in raising money for Great Ormond Street Hospital.

story: Great Ormond Street Hospital supports seriously ill children from all over the UK. Every day 619 children and young people arrive at GOSH to receive care and life saving treatments to ensure they can continue to lead healthy lives. Since 2012, Premier Inn and Restaurants have been proud partners of Great Ormond Street Hospital Charity and we know our passionate teams have taken part in many brilliant fundraising events as well as volunteering at national events around the country and at the hospital. During these uncertain times our teams continue to achieve incredible things, challenging themselves to conquer their Everest and take care of their wellbeing. We are looking to continue the fantastic fundraising achieved through our partnership by supporting our teams in their creative and dedicated ways of personal achievement. We are #innthistogether and together, we can continue our incredible work.

charity.description: We fundraise to enhance Great Ormond Street Hospital’s ability to transform the health and wellbeing of children and young people. Donations help to fund advanced medical equipment, child and family support services, pioneering research and rebuilding and refurbishment.
charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 50 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). Your donations will support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work which has a very strong meaning to Charlie and our family.

As many of you know Charlie was born unexpectedly with complex heart defects. At just 1 day old he was transferred with blue lights to GOSH in which they completely saved his life. Keeping a very poorly baby alive for 9 days before he received his first open heart surgery and then his second at 6 months old.

Unfortunately Charlie’s heart cannot be fixed and therefore he will need more heart surgeries in the coming years and require the ongoing care from GOSH for the rest of his life.

We will forever be grateful to all of the staff at GOSH for giving us the time with our amazing little man that was very nearly taken away from us. So we would like to raise as much money as we can for them now and in future events.

It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!

GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever. Thank you in advance!

story:
2020 was such a terrible year for so many people and that’s why I’ve decided to do what ever I can to help people in 2021. Therefore, I am setting myself the challenge to try and raise money for different charities throughout the year.

This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most.

I never liked running but my friend wanted to achieve couch to 5k and I said I would join her for moral support. Our goal was to be able to reach 5k by Christmas but it didn’t happen, oops. So for us to be able to complete our challenge of getting to 5k I figured this was a good way to help us, and doing it for charity makes it even more worth while. 

I don’t have a personal connection to Great Ormond Street Hospital but children are our future so let’s help them! Please help me in raising money for such a great charity. GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

story:
I was born with a cleft lip and pallet. I am so grateful for all GOSH have done for me and I want to raise some money to help support and ensure that kids all around the world have the care, support and treatment that I was so lucky to receive! I am 11 years old and will be a GOSH patient till I am 18 and I wish I could share my luck and all it offers me with so many more. Please help me do this!!!

Great Ormond Street Hospital Childrens Charity (GOSH Charity) and McColls, the leading neighbourhood retailer, are delighted to announce a brand-new charity partnership that aims to raise £1million over the next three years.Seriously ill children from across the UK travel to Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH) for specialist treatment for rare and complex conditions.The money raised by McColls will help fund GOSH Charitys vital parent accommodation service, supporting the refurbishment of 'McColl's House', which brings families closer together when a child is receiving treatment.By partnering with GOSH Charity, McColls colleagues and customers will support families at the heart of their communities, right across the UK.

eventName: In memory of Susan Ann  Watt
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Hi, my name is Evan. I am 7 years old. I lost my beautiful nanny last Christmas to cancer. It came rapidly and it was very aggressive.  I miss staying at my nanny’s and doing special things like strawberry picking, baking cakes, her taking me to the park, playing tennis and playing scrabble and monopoly with her. She was too young to die. I see much older people and wonder why cancer gets to some so young. I hope by raising money for cancer research it will help beat this awful disease. 

I had far too many chocolates for Christmas which I was very grateful for...however, I said to my mummy can I try and sell some of them and raise money for cancer research.

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am running 1000 miles with my dog, Rocky. I want to do it in a year, however who knows what will happen this year so I'm setting the challenge and we'll see how long it takes! 

I started on 1st January 2021 and aim ro run for 20-25 miles a week for however long it takes to get to 1000! 

I'm running to raise money for a Cancer Research UK, a charity that desperately needs funds and support, especially with fundraising events being cancelled in 2020. 

If you feel you can, please donate and check out my blog at helenfletcher50.wixsite.com

Thank you.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am running 874 miles in memory of mine and Jon’s best friend Kimberley who sadly lost her battle with cancer in October. Kimberley was just 37 and leaves behind her devoted husband Dave and 3 young children Daniel, Jarryd and Nieve 

Kimberley showed amazing bravery and strength during her illness. Her bravery has inspired me to take on this challenge and to give something back to try and help other families fighting this awful disease.

Love you loads Kimberley

story:
100k in 3 days. 

This March we will be taking to the Jurassic coast to trek 100k over 3 days in order to raise money for Cancer Research UK.

Nat:
It’s a scary thought that one in two of us will likely get some form of cancer. This is something that really hit home last year when my mum and auntie jaxs were diagnosed. 

In January Jaxs was told she had incurable brain tumour. Anyone that knew my auntie will know what an incredibly strong and determined lady she was, so it will be no surprise that even after hearing such devastating news, she rolled up her sleeves, dug in her heels and fought as hard as she could to fight this awful disease. Unfortunately this fight was one that couldn’t be won and after just 3 months her battle came to an end passing away on the 5 April.

Just 5 months after losing jaxs, mum was diagnosed with breast cancer. Although having to go through intense treatment, the prognosis is positive and she is on her way to sticking two fingers up at cancer!

We want to contribute to Cancer Research with the hope that one day no one will have to go through this. This is why we will be dusting off our walking boots and trying our best to raise as much money as possible for a great cause. So whether you can spare pennies or pounds, it will go to a fantastic cause and make a real difference. So please help us reach our target, and it will be your good deed for the day :) 

Thanks so much! 


Nat and Harri

XoX

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Hello all, well ideally I would've signed up to another cycle challenge by now, but Covid put a stop to such organised events, and my bike was stolen recently!

I've decided this year to do a series of good health challenges all while supporting Marie Curie.  My personal fitness and lifestyle has slipped terribly despite some amazing achievements in recent years, I need to be in better shape this year and I really could do with a detox of alcohol, something i'd been consuming all too casually, too often as a response to lockdowns, but really not ideal for my mental health.

Like many good causes, Marie Curie has really suffered a huge dent to income because of this pandemic, their nurses, nine UK hospices, helpline and research (they are the UK's largest charitable funder of palliative and end of life care research), and their campaigns do such an important role - each of us never know if we may need their help sometime.

Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
In June this year I will be joining my daughter, Carys, and
friends in a challenge to climb the three highest peaks in the UK: Ben Nevis, Scafell Pike and Snowdon, in just 36 hours in support of Marie Curie. This involves walking a total of 25 miles and climbing 5,200 feet!

Since 1948, Marie Curie has been offering care and support
to people living with terminal illness, offering practical information and
emotional support, free of charge, to patients and their loved ones from the point of diagnosis to the final minutes of life and in the bereavement process. They specialise in helping people to maintain dignity and independence and often to remain at home until the end.

Please help me to help this fantastic charity to continue
their immensely important work. Any donation will be very much appreciated.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
My Nan loved swimming and she loved the seaside, so she knew how important it was that people were kept safe when they were by the sea and always appreciated the amazing work the RNLI do. Whenever we would go on holiday, she would find one of the local RNLI shops to buy something to support them (even if it wasn't something she needed), just so she could help them out. 

The RNLI is the largest charity that saves lives at sea around the coasts of the United Kingdom, the Republic of Ireland, the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man as well as on some inland waterways.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am running the Edinburgh Marathon on the 30th of May 2021 for the Royal National Lifeboat Institution (RNLI) as running has always been a passion of mine and the charity is close to my heart. 

I have suffered with my mental health for the last 24 years, more so than ever in the last 5 years. After being admitted to hospital in August 2019, with the help of medical professionals, family and friends I re-discovered my passion and strength to put my running shoes back on which helped me to cope with my mental health. However, with the impact of Covid-19 and other factors I had another set-back in August 2020 and could no longer see a positive light and wanted to end the pain. I am forever thankful for the incredible response and efforts of the team of volunteers at Stonehaven RNLI that saved my life that night. 

As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. 

More than ever we need the RNLI’s help and they need ours. I appreciate any support and donations to help this charity.

charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
Out of the blue last Christmas, Flo announced that she wanted to sell her old toys to raise money to look after the environment. She and her friends spoke to their headteacher about organising a table sale. He directed them to the school Eco Club even though they would the youngest members by two years.  Plans began to organise the table sale but COVID 19 struck and the sale never happened. 

Just before Christmas 2020, Flo found a £1 coin on the floor. It didn’t belong to anyone and as all the charity coin boxes had disappeared, she decided to donate it to the WWF.  Whilst online, she learned about the Big Winter Walk a nod decided this is what she could do to finally achieve her aim. 

Flo (and her household) plan to walk 10km in her local woods on Saturday 24th January 202.

Please donate to support Flo in her quest. 

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY…

You might notice there’s less wildlife than there used to be. I was astounded to hear that it's because half of all UK species are in decline – we’re losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate.

Just this morning, we had a pair of beautiful Goldfinches visit our garden to feed on the bugs living in last summer's Calendula plants (that I have left in the garden over winter for this reason!). We also had a Blackcap visit too, and it's the first time I've seen either of these birds in my life! I also don't want it to be the last...

That's why I'm taking part in The Big Winter Wander this year, to reconnect with wildlife and raise much needed funds to help support WWF to campaign for the protection of our wildlife and environment, both in the UK and around the world. Follow me Instagram (@joannemoorewellness) for updates on the day (Sun 24th Jan) about how we get on!


If we act now, we can protect our health and the health of our planet.

Please donate as much as you can to this special cause, whether it's the price of a cup of coffee or a more substantial amount, it is REALLY appreciated, and you can relax in the knowledge that you'll be making a difference in the fight to restore our wildlife and environment.

My target is £500.00, but ideally I'd love to double that at least if I can!


This winter, your donations will go even further with the Government’s UK Aid Match programme. Donate before 31st January 2021 and the UK Government will match all public donations to support WWF's Land For Life project, up to £2 million.

Your donations will support WWF’s vital work both in the UK around the world, while match funds from the UK Government will go towards our Land for Life appeal.


Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.


Thanks SO MUCH for your support, it really means a lot. Please follow me on Instagram too, for updates on January 24th of my walk and what wildlife we discover! @joannemoorewellness

IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY

You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline  were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate.

By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our countrys beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world.

Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
I have chosen the Tamsin Trail in Richmond Park which is 7.3 miles long. Any family and friends are very much welcome to join me! Since its the outdoors, there’s plenty of room to social distance! If interested to join me, please private message me so I can give you details of start time and meet up point etc. Thank you!

It is no secret how the outdoors has become such a huge part of all our lives at the moment during this difficult time. When covid19 lockdown happened and having to self-isolate for most of April, I have come to realise how much I crave for nature and how much we all needed it (for our overall wellbeing) so here I am doing my bit to hopefully make even just a small difference for Mother Nature and the wildlife. For my kid and other children’s future as well. They deserve to grow up in a world with all its natural resources and wildlife intact and protected. - V x

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.

Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. 

Together, we won't live with poverty.

charity.name: Oxfam
story:
As a family, our 2021 goal is to be become fitter, healthier and leaner, physically and mentally. We started by weighing ourselves every month during lockdown in the spring of 2020, knowing we all needed to lose a few pounds! We now want to step up our efforts, and make a change, not just to our own bodies, but also to help improve others. 

We are lucky that we have the money, time and opportunity to be able to eat what we like, and it seems absurd that we have allowed ourselves to indulge, when there are families like ours across the world that are struggling to feed themselves, through no fault of their own. 

So we will be over the year, eating more healthily, becoming more active, and engaging in conversation and action to raise awareness of the work Oxfam does. 

Thanks for supporting us and Oxfam 💫

story:
Can we cycle 5000km in 2021?

Our family has committed to ride 5000km over the calendar year 2021 in support of the efforts to distribute COVID vaccines to low-income countries.

We are raising money on behalf of UNICEF who are working with other aid organisations to help distribute the vaccines to low-income countries around the world. UNICEF also help vaccinate children against diseases such as measles & polio and supports disaster relief efforts.

Further information about UNICEF and their projects can be found on the following web pages

Keeping children safe with vaccines - Unicef UK

UNICEF to lead procurement and supply of Coronavirus vaccines - Unicef UK

Unicef UK - Children's charity - For Every Child in Danger

Thank you for your support.

The Whitwells

charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

My beautiful, sweet, kind and amazing mother passed away 30 days ago. From sunrise to sunset there is not a moment goes by without thinking of her. Going through the biggest pain in my life and knowing that I have to keep going for my family and friends, I have decided to do a full marathon for the first time ever, in honour and memory of my mum! 

I have stopped smoking and I’m currently sticking to a gruelling 16 week training programme. I feel both mentally and physically stronger each day, knowing my mum is watching me.

My mum was a teacher for over 45 years and dedicated her whole life to educating children of all ages, often in her own time and at her own cost. She just loved making people and especially children happy! She was an idol to so many of her students and touched so many lives.

United Nations Children’s Fund (UNICEF) was always a charity very close to her heart, supporting the lives and eduction of children around the world less fortunate than ours. She believed eduction for every child around the world should be a given in today’s world.  

Thank you to all of you that have been a tremendous support to me and my family.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
I'm running the 2020 Royal Parks Half Marathon. I will be fundraising for Unicef. Unicef needs your help to support children around the world. The coronavirus pandemic is the most urgent crisis affecting children since the Second World War, upending children’s lives everywhere, including right here in the UK.

In July 2020, Unicef launched its first ever domestic response, in partnership with Sustain: the alliance for better food and farming, to ensure families can access food through local community projects.

Your donation will help to provide children life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection. Please, help me smash their fundraising targets and help children worldwide. Your donation will make a difference. Please donate what ever you can to my fundraiser for Unicef UK. 

With your help, we can build a safer world for children. Thank you

story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk

story:
Not only is Just Water the ultimate detox after an over-indulgent Christmas, but by fundraising for WaterAid you'll be helping to change lives with the gift of clean water. 

Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across the world. 

If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk

charity.name: WaterAid
story:
Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in climate-vulnerable communities.

I was inspired to raise money for clean water after watching something on You Tube. It blew my mind that parents are giving their children water that could cause them significant illness and even death. Men and women are walking miles and miles to get water that’s not even safe to drink because they have no other option. I would love to raise a little bit of money to support water aid, in providing clean water to those who don’t have this basic necessity. If you have a few spare pounds I would be so grateful if you can give. I’m no runner, so I will aim to be able to run the full 5K by the end (or hopefully before!).
